CLOSE

Lyon County logo (Photo: Lyon County)

A declaration of emergency was declared Monday by Lyon County commissioners.

The declaration:

Cancels all Citizen Advisory Board meetings until April 30;

Closes the Dayton, Stagecoach, Silver Springs, Silver City and Smith Valley community centers until April 6;

Closes all county libraries through April 6;

Closes the county’s senior centers through April 6 and develops a process to feed seniors through Meals on Wheels or a drive-up meal program;

Suspends events at the Lyon County Fairgrounds and Dayton Valley Event Center until April 6;

Limits any public meetings held at the Greg Hunewill Commission Chambers to no more than 30 people per meeting; and

Limits the hiring of replacement positions except essential positions;

Approves paid administrative leave for employees who miss normally-scheduled work time for reasons related to coronavirus;

Suspends purchases by county departments unless they are critical;

Enacts Center for Disease Control and state guidelines for access to public buildings, information sharing, employee training and other COVID-19 guidelines;

And allows the county manager to suspend operations of any non-mandated services or departments.

“I absolutely hate having to do this, but it is what it is,” Commissioner Bob Hastings said. “We have to protect our citizens.”

The county has also suspended notary services, is requiring appointments for any matter that must be addressed at the county building and has shuttered animal services and the cooperative extension office.

Two Lyon County residents who were on board the Grand Princess cruise ship are being quarantined in their homes. A third person identified with the virus while in Lyon County is being isolated at his home in Washoe County.

